Location:
Kosharitsa is a resort (Burgas region, Nessebar municipality) located 3 km from the popular resort of Sunny Beach, at the foot of the majestic Balkan Mountains, whose last slopes gently descend into the crystal-clear waters of the Black Sea. The area is picturesque, with beautiful panoramic views, nestled in dense Mediterranean vegetation. The village offers excellent conditions for relaxation and tourism.

The first archaeological finds date back to the Thracian period, later Slavs and Proto-Bulgarians settled here, and valuable Roman artifacts have also been discovered. The present settlement was founded at the beginning of the 19th century. One of the founders of the village is considered to be Grandfather Ivan and his descendants, who settled in the area of today’s Kosharitsa in 1846. The name Kosharitsa came later. Its root comes from "koshera," meaning sheepfold, where farmers raised their livestock. Livestock farming was the main source of income for the residents of the settlement.

Today, the village is extremely charming, having preserved its purity and beauty. Harmony, beauty, and tranquility of untouched nature prevail here. In the vicinity, there is the popular and lively Sunny Beach resort and the picturesque Kalinata nature reserve. The area offers excellent opportunities for both beach lovers and those seeking vibrant nightlife (in Sunny Beach). Those who seek peace can take walks in the forest. The area is perfect for cycling. Numerous eco-routes offer the opportunity for eco-tourism and mountain hiking. The nearby reservoirs will delight anglers, while the dense forest is perfect for hunting.

Kosharitsa is located 100 meters above sea level. The beach and the Sunny Beach resort are 3 km away, Burgas city and the international airport are 40 km away, and Varna is about 90 km away. The village has a school, shops, and a beautiful church in the center. The streets are paved, and there is central water supply and sewage, along with telephone and internet connections. Kosharitsa Day is celebrated on November 1st, the day of Saint Ivan Rilski.

